Short version: Food is good, but you'll be openly judged on your tipping at the end of your meal.  We have been here multiple times before on our visit to DC since the food is so good, and in the past we have tipped when the bill came. This time we both paid, but didn't tip as service was meh and we both have been spending a lot lately. We paid the bill exactly as it stated. We do this from time to time and have never had someone comment on it. The server here came out to us with our bill asking for a tip. She asked if the food was okay, and when we said yes she said "So I can add a tip to your bills then, or...?" We just stared at her. She went "Okay >:(" and stormed off. I went to use the bathroom, and apparently while I was in there the server went and got the manager who then also demanded a tip from us. Uh, no. That's a good way to lose business. I work at a cafe, and where I work it's sort of expected that you tip, but nobody gets upset if you don't. It's a bonus. Plenty of people don't tip. It's like 60%-70% that do. We aren't going to judge someone or hunt them down and demand that they tip us. That's ridiculous. Pay your employees a decent wage and don't expect people who might not be able to afford to tip to pay the employees for you.

Food is reasonably priced and the quality is certainly unquestionable. So much so that I would patronize this establishment multiple times a week. However on 4/24/18 around 1pm while on my lunch break I visited Beau Thai to pick up my take out order. Upon arrival I walked to the register as I always do to pay. I payed for my meal and decided to sit at the bar to eat and finish my lunch break. Once at the bar the slightest request for things such as soy sauce were in my opinion painful to the female server. Almost as if I was bothering her by sitting at the bar and asking for what I needed. I asked for a ginger ale and it took literally 5 minutes to be told something is wrong with the machine. I requested coke, she replied “you know it’s three dollars” to my reply “yeah I know I come here often”. Fast forward I finish my meal and gather my trash and walked to the host desk and asked if there’s a trash can go dispose of my items. Her response was “did you pay for your soda?” What kind of question is that to be asked... really a soda? Mind you the 3 dollars and thirty cents were on the bar inside of the sleeve. I was shocked to be asked about a soda that I clearly paid for and had the server payed attention she would’ve known. My response was “did you really ask me did I pay for a soda?” “Yeah it’s on the bar, don’t ask a customer if they paid for a three dollar soda”. Completely unprofessional and this is the first time I’ve ever had an encounter similar to this at Beau Thai. I advised the manager Bob who in essence brushed it off and was nonchalant. Asking “well do you want a three dollar gift certificate?” Ummm no how about an apology to a customer who frequents your establishment. They’ve lost a customer. Mind you I was in my city government uniform. So the issue of covering a three dollar tab is pretty nonexistent and silly also weighing in the fact that I paid for my take out order prior to and just decided to sit at the bar to eat it. Never again!

Beau Thai has two locations in DC and though I prefer the Mt Pleasant location, this one ain't bad. It's on 7th Street NW in Shaw close to the original Compass Coffee. This location is spacious and you can always find a table. Unlike many nearby restaurants, Beau Thai is open for lunch (winning). Honestly, my go to always is green chicken curry and Thai iced tea. Both are tasty!

Decent place if you enjoy Americanized,  dumbed-down Thai food. Beau Thai (or should I say "Faux Thai") has gone the way of so many other "Thai" establishments in DC by dumbing down a great world cuisine in order to cater to the masses. Dishes are generally too sweet and lack the spicy/salty/sour balance that characterizes good, authentic Thai food. Drinks are a bit overpriced outside of happy hour.  Go to Baan Thai on 14th or Thai Square in Arlington if you want real-deal Thai food.
